To comprehend the role of photothermal heat in augmenting the photocatalytic hydrogen production within this composite system, the photocatalytic H2 production performance of the prepared samples was evaluated at various temperatures. As provided in Fig. 5
                        a-c, the H2 production of BCN, PCNVs, and CDs/PCNVs-3 exhibited a substantial increase with rising temperature under uncontrolled temperature conditions (RT), in contrast to cases where the temperature was controlled by circulating condensate (5, 15, and 25 °C). This observation suggests that the catalytic activities of BCN, PCNVs, and CDs/PCNVs-3 are highly responsive to variations in reaction temperature. Furthermore, to elucidate the photothermal effect, the temperature change of the solution containing the prepared samples was monitored using infrared thermography at 30 min intervals during the reaction (Fig. 5d-f). In the absence of any photocatalyst, the reaction solution of temperature exhibited no significant upward trend after 2 h of AM 1.5 G irradiation (Fig.S9), affirming that the catalyst induced the observed temperature changes. As depicted in Fig. 5d, the temperature difference in the BCN reaction solution increased modestly from 17.9 ℃ to 20.7 ℃ after 2 h of irradiation. In contrast, the temperature of the PCNVs reaction system reached 30.6 ℃, highlighting the effective enhancement in the local reaction system's temperature facilitated by the nanoreactor of cavity design. Regarding the final temperature achieved in CDs/PCNVs-3 (45.6 ℃, Fig. 5f), it becomes evident that the generated CDs significantly contribute to the photothermal aspects of the reaction system. The enhanced mobility of water molecules surrounding the high-temperature CDs/PCNVs-3 nanoreactor facilitates increased encounters between carriers, reactive radicals, and reactant molecules, which significantly improves the photocatalytic reaction rate by promoting local mass transfer kinetics [28]. In order to investigate the contribution of the photothermal effect to the activation of hydrogen–oxygen bonding in absorbed water, the relative kinetics of the photothermal-assisted photocatalytic hydrogen precipitation process were systematically investigated. The dependence of the photocatalytic H2 precipitation rate on the reaction temperature was aptly fitted to a straight line according to the Arrhenius formula [71], and the apparent activation energy (Ea
                        ) was obtained from the slope. Impressively, CDs/PCNVs-3 (35.39 kJ mol−1) compared to PCNVs (41.86 kJ mol−1) (Fig. 5g), signifying that the CDs-induced photothermal effect significantly accelerates the rate-limiting step of hydrogen evolution [72]. Furthermore, the carrier concentration of the prepared photocatalysts was discerned by analyzing the Mott-Schottky (MS) plots under dark and light conditions [73]. In Fig. 5h, the slope of CDs/PCNVs-3 is smaller under light irradiation, but this is not significant for PCNVs. The smaller values of the slopes are associated with larger carrier concentrations, which suggests that the CDs-induced photothermal effect can effectively enhance the carrier concentration of CDs/PCNVs-3 [74–76]. To evaluate the effect of the cascade electric field on charge separation and transfer, carrier densities (ND) of different catalysts were determined based on the MS curves (Fig. 5i). Calculated based on the linear slopes of the M−S plots, the ND values for PCNVs samples in darkness and illumination were 2.16 × 1021 and 2.21 × 1021 cm−3, respectively. Conversely, the ND values for CDs/PCNVs-3 samples were 5.22 × 1021 and 7.4 × 1021 cm−3 in darkness and light, respectively, indicating that the introduction of CDs effectively accelerated the separation and transfer of photo-generated charge carriers in both volume and surface regions [77]. To further corroborate the impact of photothermal effects on photogenerated charge, photochemical tests were carried out on CDs/PCNNVs-3 nanoreactors at different temperatures. As depicted in Fig. 5j and k, the higher the photocurrent intensity and the lower the impedance, which is attributed to the fact that higher temperatures can effectively enhance the excitation of the photogenerated electron-hole pairs, promote carrier separation and transfer, and significant inhibition of their recombination at elevated temperatures [78]. Additionally, the influence of photothermal effect on carrier separation and transport was further confirmed by adding 808 nm excitation to the PL emission intensity experiment. As presented in Fig. 5l, the signal intensity of the PL for CDs/PCNVs-3 under 360 nm and 808 nm dual-wavelength excitation was markedly reduced, indicating that the CDs-induced photothermal effect in CDs/PCNVs composite promotes rapid carrier migration [79].
